    <h1>BROADLEAF PLAN&#xAD;TAIN, WA&#xAD;TER LEAF AND MADEIRA-VINE ARE ED&#xAD;I&#xAD;BLE PLANTS</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201121/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-21"><time>2020-11-21</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | DESIGN</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>What are the names of these plants (above) and can they be eaten? Also, can the tu­bers of the climber be con­sumed?</p>
    <p>Agatha Teo</p>
    <p>The plant (Photo 1) is a Plan­tago species, likely Plan­tago ma­jor, which is com­monly known as the Broadleaf Plan­tain. It can oc­cur as a weed, grow­ing in com­pacted, wet soils. Its young leaves can be eaten and the plant has medic­i­nal uses.</p>
    <p>The plant in the mid­dle (Photo 2) has com­mon names such as Earth Gin­seng or Wa­ter Leaf. Its botan­i­cal name is Tal­inum fru­ti­co­sum.</p>
    <p>Its leaves can be con­sumed but must be cooked thor­oughly to re­duce their cal­cium ox­alate con­tent. The cooked leaves have a slimy tex­ture. The swollen tap root is also used in tra­di­tional medicine.</p>
    <p>The vin­ing plant (Photo 3) is botan­i­cally known as Anred­era cordi­fo­lia. Its com­mon name is Madeiravin­e and its leaves are eaten as a veg­etable where they have a slimy tex­ture.</p>
    <p>The air bul­bils are not known to be eaten. The plant pro­duces large un­der­ground tu­bers which, on the other hand, can be con­sumed.</p>

